{"id":"1504.03231","submitter":"Elias Okon","authors":"E. Okon and D. Sudarsky","title":"The Consistent Histories Formalism and the Measurement Problem","comments":"15 pages","journal-ref":"Stud. Hist. Phil. Mod. Phys. 52 (2015) 217-222","doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"quant-ph physics.hist-ph","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  In response to a recent rebuttal of [1] presented in [2], we defend the claim\nthat the Consistent Histories formulation of quantum mechanics does not solve\nthe measurement problem. In order to do so, we argue that satisfactory\nsolutions to the problem must not only not contain anthropomorphic terms (such\nas measurement or observer) at the fundamental level, but also that\napplications of the formalism to concrete situations (e.g., measurements)\nshould not require any input not contained in the description of the situation\nat hand at the fundamental level. Our assertion is that the Consistent\nHistories formalism does not meet the second criterion. We also argue that the\nso-called second measurement problem, i.e., the inability to explain how an\nexperimental result is related to a property possessed by the measured system\nbefore the measurement took place, is only a pseudo-problem. As a result, we\nreject the claim, defended in [2], that the capacity of the Consistent\nHistories formalism to solve it should count as an advantage over other\ninterpretations.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Mon, 13 Apr 2015 16:00:17 GMT"}],"update_date":"2016-06-07"}
